1
00:02:15,452 --> 00:02:20,452
Subtitles by Ankit Bhageria

2
00:02:22,453 --> 00:02:27,032
When he didn't come to the office,
10:30, 11:00...

3
00:02:28,584 --> 00:02:30,624
...I called the house.

4
00:02:30,795 --> 00:02:32,123
Catharine...

5
00:02:32,672 --> 00:02:35,957
...he went in his sleep,
so peacefully.

6
00:02:37,134 --> 00:02:39,460
The doctor said if you slept
next to him...

7
00:02:39,637 --> 00:02:42,258
...you wouldn't even have known.

8
00:02:42,598 --> 00:02:45,552
You couldn't have done anything.

9
00:02:56,821 --> 00:02:58,897
Mrs. Petersen.

10
00:02:59,156 --> 00:03:02,442
- Catharine, let me come up with you.
- No.

11
00:03:02,618 --> 00:03:05,191
You get some rest, Sara.

12
00:05:20,630 --> 00:05:23,299
Nice blouse, Alex.
- Has been for years, Michael.

13
00:05:23,466 --> 00:05:26,633
I'm late. I spent the whole morning
going over obituaries.

14
00:05:26,803 --> 00:05:28,345
The whole morning?

15
00:05:28,513 --> 00:05:31,383
<i>Yeah. Detroit Free Press on your list?
April 12th.</i>

16
00:05:31,557 --> 00:05:34,760
I don't roll out of bed
and read obituaries before coffee.

17
00:05:34,936 --> 00:05:38,305
Wasn't this guy a capo for Marangano
a few years back?

18
00:05:38,481 --> 00:05:39,809
- So?
- So...

19
00:05:39,982 --> 00:05:43,766
...two guys die within four days
of each other. What does that say?

20
00:05:43,945 --> 00:05:47,989
No pattern. This guy could've been
a hit, but Marangano died in his sleep.

21
00:05:48,157 --> 00:05:50,482
He stopped breathing.
They ran a full...

22
00:05:50,660 --> 00:05:52,486
- Not now.
Is that what Bruce thinks?

23
00:05:52,662 --> 00:05:53,693
Alex.

24
00:05:53,871 --> 00:05:58,035
A government pouch to someone's
home is illegal. Worse, it's expensive.

25
00:05:58,209 --> 00:06:01,827
Well, my contribution
to the federal deficit.

26
00:06:04,799 --> 00:06:09,544
And let go of this Marangano thing.
People die in their sleep. Even dons.

27
00:06:09,720 --> 00:06:11,677
It was a hit!
Hey, keep it down.

28
00:06:11,847 --> 00:06:14,172
He ran trash collection
for half of Jersey.

29
00:06:14,350 --> 00:06:17,019
- You don't die in your sleep of...
Ondine's Curse.

30
00:06:17,186 --> 00:06:20,851
"Damage of unknown origin to the part
of the brain that controls breathing."

31
00:06:21,023 --> 00:06:22,850
It's rare. It's real. It happens.

32
00:06:23,275 --> 00:06:27,854
Yeah, I'm here six years, it never
happened. You do a run on it?

33
00:06:31,700 --> 00:06:34,072
- This the only one?
- It can't be connected.

34
00:06:34,244 --> 00:06:38,408
This guy's not Mafia. He's some
millionaire publisher from New York.

35
00:06:38,582 --> 00:06:39,910
"Cause of death unknown.

36
00:06:40,083 --> 00:06:43,120
Evidence suggests unexplained
interruption of breathing.

37
00:06:43,295 --> 00:06:45,584
Consider possibility of Ondine's Curse.

38
00:06:45,756 --> 00:06:50,501
Sam Petersen, age 60. Survived
by his wife of four months, Catharine...

39
00:06:50,677 --> 00:06:55,007
...age 31."
- And I had to go back a year to get that.

40
00:06:56,433 --> 00:07:01,676
Alex, it's the only one. Believe me.
Believe me, there's nothing there.

41
00:07:17,412 --> 00:07:20,863
I've got it sitting right here
in front of me.

42
00:07:21,041 --> 00:07:25,703
Walter, you see, I don't know how
to read the goddamn instructions.

43
00:07:25,879 --> 00:07:29,129
I'm only 5 fucking years old.

44
00:07:29,299 --> 00:07:33,795
Now, you be my daddy,
and you tell me how to use it.

45
00:07:33,970 --> 00:07:36,592
Nice and simple.

46
00:07:37,182 --> 00:07:42,603
Oh, you're goddamn right I'm serious.
But my bride is here for our luncheon.

47
00:07:42,771 --> 00:07:45,688
Well, I've never been
anybody's daddy neither.

48
00:07:45,857 --> 00:07:50,685
But if you want me to pop for 200,000
units of this little plastic turd here...

49
00:07:50,862 --> 00:07:53,270
...I suggest that you start faking it.

50
00:07:53,948 --> 00:07:58,028
<i>How's that wife of yours?
- She don't look so good today.</i>

51
00:07:58,203 --> 00:08:01,702
<i>- She's the best-looking gal in Dallas.
- She looks kind of scrag.</i>

52
00:08:01,873 --> 00:08:04,280
<i>Scraggly, my ass.</i>

53
00:08:04,792 --> 00:08:07,248
Write some of these instructions
in English.

54
00:08:07,420 --> 00:08:10,587
<i>- Maybe you can find a market for this.
- I'm on top of it.</i>

55
00:08:10,757 --> 00:08:13,841
Yeah, okay, yeah. So long, then.

56
00:08:15,595 --> 00:08:19,806
Marielle, you think anybody's gonna
be interested in a thing like this?

57
00:08:19,974 --> 00:08:25,265
It's about winning, Ben.
Everybody's interested in winning.

58
00:08:25,438 --> 00:08:28,107
They forgot that they're
making this toy for kids.

59
00:08:28,274 --> 00:08:31,228
The instructions are too complicated.

60
00:08:35,198 --> 00:08:36,858
Hot damn!

61
00:09:57,613 --> 00:10:00,530
I gotta be the world's
number one airhead.

62
00:10:00,699 --> 00:10:04,910
Be gone five days, and I'm packing
half of Neiman Marcus here.

63
00:10:07,414 --> 00:10:08,742
Marielle?

64
00:10:08,915 --> 00:10:10,742
Yeah, hon?

65
00:10:11,793 --> 00:10:14,331
How come we run out of brandy
so quick, hon?

66
00:10:14,796 --> 00:10:18,046
Didn't I see a fresh bottle
in the cabinet?

67
00:10:28,143 --> 00:10:30,432
Right again, hon.

68
00:10:50,081 --> 00:10:55,870
Marielle, I've explained to Etta
that this will is valid in all respects.

69
00:10:56,045 --> 00:11:00,423
Any contest here would just be
a waste of time and money.

70
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:02,508
My time.

71
00:11:02,677 --> 00:11:04,171
My money.

72
00:11:05,054 --> 00:11:10,345
What, a man cuts his only sister out of
his will two months after marrying a...?

73
00:11:10,518 --> 00:11:12,096
Younger woman?

74
00:11:14,314 --> 00:11:17,480
You know something, Etta,
your husband is right.

75
00:11:17,650 --> 00:11:20,022
Ben had no quarrel with you.

76
00:11:20,194 --> 00:11:23,444
Only the way you felt about me.

77
00:11:24,532 --> 00:11:27,403
I think, if he were here...

78
00:11:28,077 --> 00:11:31,161
...he'd regret what he'd done.

79
00:11:35,042 --> 00:11:36,869
Martin?

80
00:11:37,044 --> 00:11:39,915
What are the tax consequences
if I make a small gift?

81
00:11:40,089 --> 00:11:42,331
Young lady...

82
00:11:43,342 --> 00:11:47,174
Marielle is going to go back
to Charleston...

83
00:11:47,346 --> 00:11:52,803
...and she doesn't want any
harsh feelings or needless delays.

84
00:11:53,936 --> 00:11:57,186
How small a gift, dear?

85
00:12:03,154 --> 00:12:06,605
Something in the mid-six figures?

86
00:12:18,252 --> 00:12:21,621
Miss Barnes! Miss Barnes?

87
00:12:21,797 --> 00:12:24,798
Miss Barnes, can I look
in your purse, please?

88
00:12:28,095 --> 00:12:29,969
Here she comes!

89
00:12:39,481 --> 00:12:41,937
What? You gonna knock over
a liquor store?

90
00:12:42,109 --> 00:12:46,687
I was just at the target range.
I'm trying to get certified, that's all.

91
00:12:47,489 --> 00:12:51,403
I tell you what.
Send the piece back to Sears.

92
00:12:56,665 --> 00:12:58,622
Remember that Ondine's Curse thing?

93
00:13:02,713 --> 00:13:05,382
Another one came up today.

94
00:13:05,799 --> 00:13:09,049
This guy died 10 days ago.

95
00:13:22,566 --> 00:13:23,976
Dinner?

96
00:13:24,151 --> 00:13:25,561
What?

97
00:13:25,735 --> 00:13:30,314
- I said, dinner? Eat? Tonight?
- I have work left.

98
00:13:30,490 --> 00:13:33,574
Fine. Tomorrow?

99
00:13:33,743 --> 00:13:36,910
I don't think it's a good idea.
We work together.

100
00:13:37,080 --> 00:13:40,164
What, office policy? What?

101
00:13:40,542 --> 00:13:42,997
Okay. I resign.

102
00:13:44,754 --> 00:13:47,921
I can't afford to lose you.
You're my right arm.

103
00:13:49,759 --> 00:13:51,088
Okay.

104
00:13:57,100 --> 00:13:59,721
What did you say about Ondine's Curse?

105
00:13:59,894 --> 00:14:02,219
- It's not Mafia.
- What is it?

106
00:14:02,397 --> 00:14:05,813
It's a toy manufacturer from Dallas.

107
00:14:05,984 --> 00:14:11,274
He's very rich. He's very clean.
I'll get you a printout tomorrow, okay?

108
00:14:14,659 --> 00:14:16,984
- Good night.
- Good night.

109
00:14:21,290 --> 00:14:23,248
Michael.

110
00:14:23,710 --> 00:14:25,583
Wait up.

111
00:14:25,753 --> 00:14:28,161
I'm gonna go with you.

112
00:14:31,926 --> 00:14:34,417
Could a Texas toy mogul
have a mob connection?

113
00:14:34,595 --> 00:14:37,513
The Texan's a ringer
for that other guy from New York.

114
00:14:37,682 --> 00:14:40,469
How's that?
- Well, both older guys, very rich...

115
00:14:40,643 --> 00:14:43,679
...each married to a young gal
for a couple of months.

116
00:14:43,854 --> 00:14:47,899
- Must be kind of bad for your health.
- Hey, you got a minute?

117
00:14:57,243 --> 00:15:01,240
Make some calls to New York, Dallas.
Newspapers, whatever.

118
00:15:01,414 --> 00:15:03,572
Let's round up some photos.

119
00:15:03,749 --> 00:15:07,367
Shouldn't be hard.
They were prominent guys.

120
00:15:07,962 --> 00:15:09,954
Not the men.

121
00:15:10,131 --> 00:15:12,253
The wives.

122
00:15:32,945 --> 00:15:34,273
Okay.

123
00:15:35,781 --> 00:15:39,613
Seattle guidebooks,
Japanese cooking, what next?

124
00:15:40,202 --> 00:15:43,119
- Rare coins.
- What sort of rare coins?

125
00:15:43,288 --> 00:15:49,077
Something general for the beginner, then
something more particular. Perhaps...

126
00:15:49,253 --> 00:15:50,961
...Italy, the 19th century.

127
00:15:51,129 --> 00:15:54,166
Before the city-states were unified
or after?

128
00:15:54,341 --> 00:15:57,046
I don't know.
Which would be more...

129
00:15:58,178 --> 00:16:00,634
...unusual?

130
00:16:03,183 --> 00:16:05,508
Northwest Indians. Which tribes?

131
00:16:05,686 --> 00:16:09,055
Coast Salish, for certain.
Whatever else you have.

132
00:16:09,231 --> 00:16:12,018
Tlingit, Bella Coola, Kwakiutl.

133
00:16:12,192 --> 00:16:14,398
My primary interest is in totem poles.

134
00:16:14,569 --> 00:16:17,191
What are you,
cramming for a game show?

135
00:18:22,154 --> 00:18:25,404
No, I'll take it. Thank you.

136
00:18:50,015 --> 00:18:53,799
Come here. Come here, children.
Teachers, let's move them along.

137
00:18:54,186 --> 00:18:55,810
Come this way.

138
00:19:04,446 --> 00:19:07,151
One million dollars.

139
00:19:08,617 --> 00:19:11,190
A very generous offer, Miss Dodd...

140
00:19:11,453 --> 00:19:14,454
...but this museum does not sell
places on its board.

141
00:19:14,623 --> 00:19:15,951
- Our chairman...
- Yes.

142
00:19:16,124 --> 00:19:19,956
I'm sure Mr. McCorey will appreciate
my intentions. Good day.

143
00:19:23,465 --> 00:19:26,466
But Margaret,
we want your views on this.

144
00:19:26,635 --> 00:19:30,715
Now, I understand you had very
strong feelings about this collection.

145
00:19:30,889 --> 00:19:33,296
Mr. McCorey...

146
00:19:33,475 --> 00:19:36,511
...I didn't want my first meeting
to be one where I...

147
00:19:36,686 --> 00:19:38,180
You disagreed with anybody.

148
00:19:41,274 --> 00:19:44,275
I think it's a mistake to concentrate
so exclusively...

149
00:19:44,444 --> 00:19:46,935
...on the Coast Salish in our acquisitions.

150
00:19:47,739 --> 00:19:51,819
You want to be the best at something,
but that's not our role.

151
00:19:51,993 --> 00:19:53,487
And what is, Margaret?

152
00:19:53,661 --> 00:19:56,662
We need to compare all the tribes.

153
00:19:56,831 --> 00:19:59,916
We study their art to learn about them.

154
00:20:00,084 --> 00:20:03,916
We study them
to understand ourselves.

155
00:20:09,135 --> 00:20:12,006
These the best pictures?
She doesn't want pictures.

156
00:20:12,180 --> 00:20:14,967
She knows the camera's there.
She turns away.

157
00:20:15,141 --> 00:20:17,679
The Texas one is different,
slimmer body.

158
00:20:17,852 --> 00:20:20,177
- It's the way she's stand...
- She's younger.

159
00:20:20,355 --> 00:20:23,190
- It's makeup, hair, attitude.
- I think you're wrong.

160
00:20:23,358 --> 00:20:24,900
I could be right.

161
00:20:25,234 --> 00:20:28,603
The whole m.o., a complex series
of seductions and murders...

162
00:20:28,780 --> 00:20:31,105
...that's not something
you see a woman do.

163
00:20:31,282 --> 00:20:36,110
Oh? Which part you figure a woman isn't
up to? The seduction or the murder?

164
00:20:36,287 --> 00:20:38,908
Look, I just want the field assignment.

165
00:20:39,081 --> 00:20:41,489
- Please?
- Listen...

166
00:20:41,667 --> 00:20:44,372
...data analysis is the heart
of what we do here.

167
00:20:44,545 --> 00:20:47,914
The best work in this shop
is yours. The best.

168
00:20:48,090 --> 00:20:51,590
- It's a job you were born to do.
- It's a job with green windows!

169
00:20:51,761 --> 00:20:54,548
Bruce, I've been in this office
for six years.

170
00:20:54,722 --> 00:20:57,842
This goddamned government
office with green windows.

171
00:20:58,017 --> 00:21:02,097
You want excitement. People
don't look to get it all from their job.

172
00:21:03,314 --> 00:21:05,390
- What's that supposed to mean?
- Jesus.

173
00:21:05,566 --> 00:21:08,235
What do you think it means?
Having a date!

174
00:21:08,402 --> 00:21:12,981
When was the last time you rolled in late
on a Monday because of a big weekend?

175
00:21:13,157 --> 00:21:16,490
I really can't believe
you're saying this to me!

176
00:21:16,827 --> 00:21:19,365
I have to listen to this shit
from my mother!

177
00:21:19,538 --> 00:21:22,705
What the hell do you think
you are, Bruce?

178
00:21:27,379 --> 00:21:29,419
Look, I just...

179
00:21:32,301 --> 00:21:34,874
You're not happy.

180
00:21:35,262 --> 00:21:38,216
You're not a happy person.

181
00:21:40,267 --> 00:21:42,425
And you deserve to be, that's all.

182
00:21:43,854 --> 00:21:47,353
Bruce, make me happy.

183
00:21:57,034 --> 00:21:59,951
Even if you're right, it isn't federal.

184
00:22:02,414 --> 00:22:06,079
Whatever you can't fit on the
weekends, make sure you call in sick.

185
00:22:08,879 --> 00:22:10,207
Thanks.

186
00:22:19,598 --> 00:22:23,263
She was destroyed by his death.
They were very devoted.

187
00:22:23,435 --> 00:22:27,479
Catharine needed to get away,
and she went to Europe.

188
00:22:27,647 --> 00:22:31,016
That was over a year ago.
Have you heard from her?

189
00:22:31,192 --> 00:22:35,689
I had a postcard from Rome. I had
a lovely note from Vienna, a little gift.

190
00:22:35,864 --> 00:22:40,360
All in the first month, or thereabouts.
Anything lately?

191
00:22:40,785 --> 00:22:42,612
Only the attorney.

192
00:22:42,787 --> 00:22:46,203
He received instructions
to convert the estate into cash...

193
00:22:46,499 --> 00:22:49,286
...and to transfer the funds
to a Swiss account.

194
00:22:49,461 --> 00:22:53,293
No one else in Manhattan,
not a single soul.

195
00:22:53,465 --> 00:22:56,668
Everyone says the same thing.
From Chicago, no family...

196
00:22:56,843 --> 00:23:00,259
...they don't know where she lived,
where she worked.

197
00:23:01,472 --> 00:23:03,264
Could I have this photograph?

198
00:23:08,313 --> 00:23:12,262
I'm sorry.
That must have sounded awful.

199
00:23:14,902 --> 00:23:20,110
Sara, it's just that she came out of thin
air, and she vanished back into thin air.

200
00:23:20,283 --> 00:23:24,530
- Well, is that against the law?
- It's odd. I find it odd.

201
00:23:25,663 --> 00:23:30,870
Sam Petersen is gone.
So is all of his property, his money.

202
00:23:32,295 --> 00:23:36,079
And if I loved him as much as you did,
I'd find it very odd indeed.

203
00:23:41,304 --> 00:23:46,131
That's Felice Baciocchi
and her sister Elisa.

204
00:23:48,853 --> 00:23:52,518
You probably looked all this up
just to impress me.

205
00:23:54,317 --> 00:23:56,724
Did it work?

206
00:23:57,236 --> 00:24:03,689
Well, you know, I really did wonder.
You seem almost too good to be true.

207
00:24:04,577 --> 00:24:07,494
I thought of checking up on you.

208
00:24:12,668 --> 00:24:14,791
Not a bad thought.

209
00:24:14,962 --> 00:24:18,663
After all, I could be
practically anybody.

210
00:24:19,133 --> 00:24:22,169
Dangerous not to check people out.

211
00:24:22,344 --> 00:24:24,503
I did.

212
00:24:27,057 --> 00:24:29,762
And what did you find?

213
00:24:31,228 --> 00:24:36,567
I found that you went to Mount
Holyoke, you studied anthropology...

214
00:24:36,734 --> 00:24:40,019
...and I found...

215
00:24:40,487 --> 00:24:43,192
...we're a lot alike.

216
00:24:46,994 --> 00:24:49,995
We like Italy, and we like coins.

217
00:24:50,914 --> 00:24:52,741
And we like to live alone.

218
00:24:55,961 --> 00:24:58,831
You never talk about that.

219
00:25:00,132 --> 00:25:03,133
I don't know why I never married.

220
00:25:03,302 --> 00:25:06,006
I have a serviceable list of reasons.

221
00:25:06,179 --> 00:25:11,766
Take out my reasons
and polish them every once in a while.

222
00:25:12,185 --> 00:25:15,389
I kept on growing out
in all these...

223
00:25:15,564 --> 00:25:19,727
...peculiar and idiosyncratic directions.

224
00:25:20,402 --> 00:25:24,400
I'd put on a little bristle here
and a bristle there...

225
00:25:24,573 --> 00:25:26,696
...and sort of...

226
00:25:26,867 --> 00:25:29,073
...turned myself into a porcupine.

227
00:25:31,746 --> 00:25:37,666
- What?
- Well, it's just such an old joke.

228
00:25:37,919 --> 00:25:40,208
How do two porcupines...

229
00:25:40,380 --> 00:25:42,752
...make love?

230
00:25:45,427 --> 00:25:47,633
Very carefully.

231
00:25:54,936 --> 00:25:58,720
To the left, right around this corner.
You'll find it.

232
00:26:08,908 --> 00:26:12,194
It's kind of you to make time
in your busy schedule for me.

233
00:26:12,537 --> 00:26:14,328
No trouble at all.

234
00:26:14,872 --> 00:26:18,158
So have you thought at all
about what I said?

235
00:26:18,334 --> 00:26:21,288
Uh-huh. You know something?

236
00:26:21,462 --> 00:26:24,997
That very same idea occurred to me
right after the funeral.

237
00:26:25,174 --> 00:26:27,131
I even hired a detective.

238
00:26:27,301 --> 00:26:31,595
Sent him over to Charleston,
where she said her people were at.

239
00:26:31,764 --> 00:26:35,465
There was nothing at all.
No family, not even a trace.

240
00:26:36,435 --> 00:26:39,639
